{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17598199","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17598199"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T11:34:11+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T11:34:11+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15450"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"15450","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/15450"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8141"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62889"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"8141","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/8141"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15450"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48340"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4928"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"},{"type":"tags","id":"4946"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"8127"},{"type":"tags","id":"8399"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"19730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"20502"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62889","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/62889"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anal canal contains specialised vascular structures that contribute to continence.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following statements about haemorrhoidal tissue is correct?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Haemorrhoidal vascular cushions are located at 3, 7, and 11 o\u0027clock positions","External haemorrhoids develop above the dentate line","Internal haemorrhoids are covered by keratinised epithelium","Haemorrhoidal tissue contains only arterial vessels","Haemorrhoidal cushions are pathological structures that require treatment"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe anal canal contains three main \u003Cstrong\u003Ehaemorrhoidal vascular cushions\u003C/strong\u003E located at the 3, 7, and 11 o\u0027clock positions when viewed with the patient in lithotomy position. These are normal anatomical structures that contribute to anal continence.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EExternal haemorrhoids\u003C/strong\u003E develop below (not above) the dentate line and are covered by sensitive anoderm. \u003Cstrong\u003EInternal haemorrhoids\u003C/strong\u003E develop above the dentate line and are covered by insensitive columnar epithelium, not keratinised epithelium. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhoidal tissue\u003C/strong\u003E contains both arterial and venous vessels arranged in a complex vascular plexus. \u003Cstrong\u003EHaemorrhoidal vascular cushions\u003C/strong\u003E are normal anatomical structures that only require treatment when they become symptomatic due to pathological changes.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Haemorrhoidal cushions are normal vascular structures located in three main positions within the anal canal.","Internal haemorrhoids develop from the superior haemorrhoidal plexus above the dentate line.","External haemorrhoids develop from the inferior haemorrhoidal plexus below the dentate line."],"references":["Mott T, Latimer K, Edwards C. Hemorrhoids: Diagnosis and Treatment Options. Am Fam Physician. 2018 Feb 1;97(3):172-179. PMID: 29431977.","Fontem RF, Eyvazzadeh D. Internal Hemorrhoid. [Updated 2023 Jul 31]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK537182/","Sun Z, Migaly J. Review of Hemorrhoid Disease: Presentation and Management. Clin Colon Rectal Surg. 2016 Mar;29(1):22-9. doi: 10.1055/s-0035-1568144. PMID: 26929748; PMCID: PMC4755769.","Yamada, T., Alpers, D. H., Kalloo, A. N., Kaplowitz, N., Owyang, C., \u0026 Powell, D. W. (Eds.). (2011). Textbook of gastroenterology. John Wiley \u0026 Sons","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48340"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15450"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"48340","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/48340"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-19T09:12:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-19T09:12:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8141"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"62889"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount"